      "content": "Economically, proponents argue that stricter immigration controls protect domestic wages by limiting the supply of low-skilled labor. They contend that an influx of low-cost, unauthorized workers can depress wages in sectors where the new arrivals compete directly with native-born workers. This perspective suggests that tightly managed immigration allows the domestic economy to retain its labor pool, thereby supporting the earning potential of its current workforce. Therefore, controlled entry is framed as a mechanism for wage protection and maintaining equitable labor markets.",
      "source": "target",
